         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">7/7/90. ¶  ¶ A few words, dear Prof Watson, as the monthly mail for America will be despatched to morrow. I like to follow up some remarks, formerly offered, ¶  about the advisability to distribute th...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">90.07.07</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Sereno Watson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Gray Herbarium Archives, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">7/7/90.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A few words, dear Prof Watson, as the monthly mail for America will be despatched to morrow. I like to follow up some remarks, formerly offered,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to S. Watson, 6 May 1890.</p>
               </note> about the advisability to distribute the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> among the other orders, Gymnosperms only remaining apart. Since 25 years I have done so here, and we cannot have a complete natural system, unless this is done. You will not deem me intrusive, when I say, that I speak from independent experiments of my own during 50 years! As a mere instance in support I may mention, that <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> and so also Loranthus are undoubtedly petaliferous. In Australia exists a Loranthus, my L. odontocalyx,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Published by Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, p. 391, using the specimen from M and preserving his herbarium name (see labels on K848222 and MEL2288074).</p>
               </note> which has a very conspicuous denticulation of the calyx, indeed the latter is five lobed, the lobes of course continuous with the tube; moreover, the petals of all these plants are jointed with the calyx, altho' the latter may be reduced to almost nothing as in some <name key="Rhododendron">Rhododendron</name>s, <name key="Asterolasia">Asterolasia</name>, <name key="Diplolaena">Diplolaena</name> &amp;c. I like you and Prof. Coulter to consult about this subject, not because it is my view, but because we all must strive from different material to complete a truly rational system from nearest affinities. You both have the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Second</hi>
               </seg> "Census"<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B89.12.03.</p>
               </note> and "Key".<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B86.04.05 (pt. 2) and B88.11.02 (pt. 1). </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">The valediction is in the left margin of p. 4. </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I mentioned this long ago in print though some late observers, while adopting my view, ignore my observations, well known to them.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">I mentioned … to them </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is a note in the centre margin of the sheet between pages 2 and 3, keyed with an asterisk to </seg>
                     <seg style="">… that <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name>. </seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0.1598in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">For an earlier comment on floral structure of <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> and Loranthaceae see, for example, B77.08.01, p. 52.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Kindly read the preface of the first Census.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">The sentence is in the centre margin of the front of the sheet, between pages 1 and 4.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I like to have a joint answer from both of you.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">The sentence is in the left margin of p. 2.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Consider <name key="Dodonaea">Dodonaea</name> &amp; <name key="Aesculus">Aesculus</name> together.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The sentence is on the right margin of p. 3.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
